    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided text, here are the relevant disclosures regarding the determination of fair market value, the use of 409A valuations and specialists, and the relationship between private valuations and the IPO offering price:\n\n### 1. Determination of Fair Market Value for Stock Options (409A and Third-Party Appraisals)\nThe footnotes to the plan-based awards table explicitly state that the exercise price of stock options is determined using third-party valuations in compliance with Section 409A:\n> "(3) The exercise price of each stock option granted during the 2025 Fiscal Year reflects the fair market value of a share of our Class C common stock on the date of grant and was determined based on a third-party valuation obtained in accordance with Section 409A of the Code."\n\n### 2. Use of Valuation Specialists for Equity Instruments\nIn both the critical accounting estimates section and the notes to the consolidated financial statements, the company discloses that it engages outside specialists to value its equity instruments:\n> "Amounts which are subject to significant judgment and use of estimates include... the valuation and assumptions underlying share-based compensation. On an ongoing basis, the Company evaluates its estimates compared to historical experience and current trends, which forms the basis for making judgments about the carrying value of assets and liabilities. **In addition, the Company engages valuation specialists to assist in the valuation of equity instruments.**"\n\n### 3. FASB ASC Topic 718 for Grant Date Fair Value\nThe footnotes also explain how the grant date fair value is calculated for accounting purposes:\n> "(4) Amounts in this column represent the grant date fair value of stock options and RSUs, calculated in accordance with FASB ASC Topic 718, disregarding the effect of estimated forfeitures."\n\n### 4. Relationship Between Private Valuations and the IPO Offering Price\nThe prospectus discusses the lack of a historical public market and how the IPO price was determined through negotiations rather than a formula tied to past private valuations:\n> "Prior to this offering, there has been no public market for our Class A common stock. The initial public offering price has been determined by negotiations between us and the representatives. Among the factors considered in determining the initial public offering price were prevailing market conditions, our future prospects and those of our industry in general, our historical financial and operating performance in recent periods, an assessment by our management and the consideration of the above factors in relation to market valuation of companies engaged in [similar businesses]."\n\n### 5. Limitations and Risks Regarding Public Market Pricing\nThe document warns investors about the lack of a prior public market and the potential disconnect between private expectations and public market realities:\n> "Prior to this offering, there has been no public market for our Class A common stock. Future sales of our Class A common stock in the public market, or the availability of such shares for sale in the public market, could adversely affect the market price of our Class A common stock prevailing from time to time." \n\n*(Note: While the text mentions the lack of a public market prior to the offering and the negotiation process for the IPO price, it does not contain specific risk factors comparing tender offer or secondary market prices to the IPO price within the provided chunks.)*',
